title: Faith and Philosophy in the University
author: Xavier O. Monasterio
date: undated (likely late 1960s or early 1970s)
source: Mary Brown (external contributor)
provenance: Scanned document provided by Mary Brown, January 2026
description: A 12-page essay arguing for academic freedom for Catholic philosophers. Critiques the notion of "Catholic philosophy" and the imposition of Thomism, arguing that philosophy is a rational discipline like any other science. Addresses the relationship between faith and reason, and the proper role of philosophy in the university.
topics: academic freedom, Catholic philosophy, Thomism, faith and reason, university, philosophy of religion
notes: |
  Document provided by Mary Brown, who interviewed Xavier Monasterio for her book on the UD Philosophy Department controversy. Original document described as a "purple 12-page document" titled "Faith and Philosophy in the University."

  Xavier arrived at the University of Dayton in 1966, the same year the "Heresy Affair" controversy reached its peak. This document was likely written in the aftermath of that controversy, perhaps late 1960s or early 1970s.

  Mary Brown's note (January 2026): "I knew your father. There were times when he and I met in the Chapel in the early morning hours (about 6:30 a.m.!). I also interviewed him for my book on the controversy in the UD Philosophy Department in the late 1960s."

  Mary Brown's dissertation (2003) became the book "Heresy in the Heartland: The Controversy at The University of Dayton, 1960-67" (Catholic University of America Press).
